<CONTENT id="_800668_1"><TITLE value="Topic 8.2: Linear classifiers"/><TITLECOLOR value="#000000"/><DESCRIPTION
   value=""/><BODY><TEXT>&lt;div data-layout-row="3f146f53-3ec8-4e19-959f-2b7165bd2926"&gt;&lt;div data-layout-column="85398e6c-9bd7-4980-86b3-c2a3d1bbe7e0" data-layout-column-width="12"&gt;&lt;div data-bbid="bbml-editor-id_850ed1bf-15a2-4212-80a3-0082bfe66108"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Topic 8.2: Linear classifiers&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693118_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Linear classifier cartoon image&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_Linear_Classifier_logo.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:289.8000183105469,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:385.11946552295655}"&gt;M8_Linear_Classifier_logo.png&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this topic we introduce the&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt; linear classifiers&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, due to their importance to the neural networks and actually the main activation function for the basic neural network perceptron is a linear&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt; classifier&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Watch this video then continue reading the topic:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;a href="https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/88d9373610d141629dd104e75649c13a1d" data-bbtype="video" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;src&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/88d9373610d141629dd104e75649c13a1d&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;alt&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/88d9373610d141629dd104e75649c13a1d&amp;quot;}"&gt;https://mediasite.centennialcollege.ca/Mediasite/Play/88d9373610d141629dd104e75649c13a1d&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;As noted from the video lecture note linear classifiers &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;are not&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; Linear regression nor logistic regression.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h5&gt;&lt;span style="color: #1c8845"&gt;Linear classifiers&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;Linear classifiers focus on finding a separator also called a&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;decision&amp;nbsp;boundary&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt; between the data point (observations) as per the below figure.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693119_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Decision boundary&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_ decision boundry.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:836.4000244140625,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:370.6337000952289}"&gt;M8_ decision boundry.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;A decision boundary is a is a line (or surface, in higher dimensions) that separates the two classes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;Data that admit to such a separator are called linearly separable. A weight vector is introduce and and the classification hypothesis can be introduced as follows:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;h&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;&lt;sub&gt;w&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;(x) = 1 if w.x &amp;gt;= 0 and 0 otherwise&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;In order to do they have the following&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt; activation function&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693120_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;PastedImage_ejba8cif3jc7bzimicgpruziketdf6ef001101512785.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;PastedImage_ejba8cif3jc7bzimicgpruziketdf6ef001101512785.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Before we move forward in explaining, we need to look at this formula and as you have noticed there is the vector dot product. &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;w&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;.f&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;&lt;sub&gt;i&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 1.125rem;"&gt;(x)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt; .where &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;w&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is the weight vector and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;x&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the feature vector.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693121_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;why dot product&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_Geometric.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:705,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:332.5471698113207}"&gt;M8_Geometric.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;Let first explain a bit about vectors.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h5&gt;&lt;span style="color: #1c8845"&gt;Vectors&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;The following three (x,y) points plotted on a 2D space would look like this:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;(1,2), (3,4), (-2,3)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693122_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;2D plot of three points&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_vectors_example.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:772.1625366210938,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:378.44129396897387}"&gt;M8_vectors_example.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Notice that each point in addition to magnitude (length) will have a direction. The point (1,2) points in the same direction as point (3,4), while the third point (-2,3) point ins a different direction. Linear classifiers uses this as a base to set the decision boundary.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This falls under mathematical geometry.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Let's have a look at the below diagram that reflects two vectors A &amp;amp; B:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693123_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Two vectors A &amp;amp; B&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_two_vectors.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M8_two_vectors.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The values |A| and |B| represent the lengths of vectors A and B, respectively, and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;Θ&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the angle between the two vectors. The dot product of vectors A and B will have the following relationship to these values:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;span style="color: #1c8845"&gt;A · B = |A| * |B| * cos(Θ)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Angular Domain of &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dot Product&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;If A and B &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;are perpendicular&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (at 90 degrees to each other), the result of the dot product will be zero, because cos(Θ) will be zero.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;If the angle between A and B is &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;less than 90 degrees&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, the dot product will be positive (greater than zero), as cos(Θ) will be positive.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;If the angle between A and B is &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;greater than 90 degrees&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, the dot product will be negative (less than zero), as cos(Θ) will be negative.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;h6&gt;&lt;span style="color: #1c8845"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Linear classifiers&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h6&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;Linear classifiers builds on the dot product concept in identifying the decision boundary between the observed data points.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;This is best clarified through an example. Have a look at the below image of our agent trying to identify spam from ham e-mails:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693124_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Agent filtering spam e-mails&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_Spam-ham.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:586,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:232.9879518072289}"&gt;M8_Spam-ham.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;The figure below shows two spam e-mails:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693125_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Examples of spam e-mails&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_example of spam e-mail.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:856.4000244140625,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:295.5519210085263}"&gt;M8_example of spam e-mail.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;Looking at the feature space of this problem, the subject matter experts might come up with many ideas, for example if the word "free" was mentioned, or if the amounts in the e-mail had big variances, or if there were many spelling mistakes, etc., each of these features can be assigned a weight based on its importance. For example the word "free" might be considered as the first feature &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;x&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt; and assigned a high weight &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;w&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt; value 4.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;The below figure illustrates an example of one e-mail:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693126_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Feature space for e-mails&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_feature space_spam .png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:771.4000244140625,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:238.51406148024435}"&gt;M8_feature space_spam .png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Accordingly, each e-mail will go through a check and weights are assigned based on the presence and frequencies of each feature. A &lt;strong&gt;weight vector&lt;/strong&gt; is set and can be drawn in the space and then the observations, i.e. e-mails from the training, are compared by looking at the angular difference of the dot product, the figure below shows two training examples, their vectors are in red and the weight vector in black, the decision boundary is in pink and perpendicular to the weight vector:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693127_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Weight vector&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_weight_vector.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M8_weight_vector.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;If the weight vector and the feature vector point in the same direction then we issue a positive output. Else, we amend the weight vector.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dot product:&lt;/strong&gt; we can get the angle between the vectors&amp;nbsp;positive means the positive class.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693128_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;separator&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_decision boundry.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M8_decision boundry.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The above figure illustrates the decision boundary, and notice that we add the bias to the training examples to be able to shift the boundary from the origin.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;Learning the weight vector:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693129_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Weight update &amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_weight_update.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:564,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:281.27319587628864}"&gt;M8_weight_update.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Start with weights = &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;0&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For each&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt; training instance:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Classify with current weights:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;y=&amp;nbsp;1&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;if&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;w.f(x)+bias &amp;gt;= 0&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;y = 0&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;if&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;w.f(x)+bias&amp;nbsp;&amp;lt;&amp;nbsp;0&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693130_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;weight update step1&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_weight_1.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M8_weight_1.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;If correct (i.e., y=y*), no change!&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693131_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Weight update step 2&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_weight_2.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M8_weight_2.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;If wrong:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Adjust the weight vector by adding or subtracting the feature vector. Subtract if y* is 0.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;w&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;←&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;w&amp;nbsp;± y*.f&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693132_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;Weight update step 3&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_weight_3.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;}"&gt;M8_weight_3.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The figure below illustrates an example:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="@X@EmbeddedFile.requestUrlStub@X@bbcswebdav/xid-1693133_1" data-bbtype="attachment" data-bbfile="{&amp;quot;alternativeText&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;weight update example&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;linkName&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;M8_weight_update_example.png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;mimeType&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;image/png&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;render&amp;quot;:&amp;quot;inline&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;width&amp;quot;:882,&amp;quot;height&amp;quot;:295.7093023255814}"&gt;M8_weight_update_example.png&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;f(x) is the feature vector for a data point with positive class (y* =+1) that is currently mis-classified – it lies on the wrong side of the decision boundary defined by “old w”.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Adding it to the weight vector produces a new weight vector which has a smaller angle to f(x). It also shifts the decision boundary (the dashed blue line).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;h5&gt;References&lt;/h5&gt;&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;Chapter 19 &lt;span style="color: #000000"&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Open Sans;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;Artificial intelligence a modern approach&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Open Sans;"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 0.875rem;"&gt;by Stuart J. Russell and Peter Norvig,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;UC Berkeley CS188 Intro to AI&amp;nbsp;&lt;a href="http://ai.berkeley.edu/home.html"&gt;http://ai.berkeley.edu/home.html&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.mvps.org/DirectX/articles/math/dot/index.htm"&gt;http://www.mvps.org/DirectX/articles/math/dot/index.htm#:~:text=If%20the%20angle%20between%20A%20and%20B%20are%20greater%20than,lengths%20are%20always%20positive%20values&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href="https://jamestfang.com/notes/188/n10.pdf"&gt;https://jamestfang.com/notes/188/n10.pdf&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</TEXT><TYPE
